Document Chat Assistant — Architecture, Hierarchy & Step-by-Step Build

Purpose

This document describes the system hierarchy, the exact step-by-step process used to build the project, which technologies were used at each step, implementation notes, and example applications. Use this as a reproducible guide for future developers.

1. System Hierarchy (components and responsibilities)

- Frontend (React + Vite)
  - Entry: [frontend/index.html](frontend/index.html#L1)
  - App container: [frontend/src/App.jsx](frontend/src/App.jsx#L1-L120)
  - Components:
    - File upload UI: [frontend/src/components/FileUpload.jsx](frontend/src/components/FileUpload.jsx#L1-L200)
    - Chat UI: [frontend/src/components/ChatBox.jsx](frontend/src/components/ChatBox.jsx#L1-L200)
  - Responsibilities: user interactions, file selection, uploading to backend, showing chat history, sending questions.

- Backend (Node.js + Express)
  - Entry: [backend/src/server.js](backend/src/server.js#L1-L60)
  - Routers:
    - Upload: [backend/src/routes/upload.js](backend/src/routes/upload.js#L1-L200)
    - Query: [backend/src/routes/query.js](backend/src/routes/query.js#L1-L200)
    - Files: [backend/src/routes/files.js](backend/src/routes/files.js#L1-L200)
  - Services:
    - Document parsing: [backend/src/services/documentParser.js](backend/src/services/documentParser.js#L1-L300)
    - Retrieval & chunking: [backend/src/services/retrievalService.js](backend/src/services/retrievalService.js#L1-L300)
    - Embeddings wrapper: [backend/src/services/embeddingService.js](backend/src/services/embeddingService.js#L1-L200)
    - LLM orchestration: [backend/src/services/llmService.js](backend/src/services/llmService.js#L1-L300)
    - Structured answerer (CSV/table queries): [backend/src/services/structuredAnswerService.js](backend/src/services/structuredAnswerService.js#L1-L400)
  - DB layer: [backend/src/db.js](backend/src/db.js#L1-L200)

- Storage
  - SQLite file: `backend/data/app.db` (created by `initDb()` in `db.js`)
  - Tables: `documents`, `document_chunks`, `chats`

2. Step-by-step Build & Tech Mapping

Step 0 — Prerequisites
- Tools: Node.js 18+, npm
- Optional: OpenAI API key for embeddings and LLM responses
- Files edited/created: none
- How to verify: `node -v` and `npm -v`

Step 1 — Initialize project structure (already present)
- Tech: file system, Node.js project layout
- Implementation: two folders `backend/` and `frontend/` with `package.json` files.
- Why: separate concerns; backend exposes REST API, frontend is static SPA served by Vite.

Step 2 — Backend basics (Express app & DB init)
- Tech: Node.js, Express, sqlite, sqlite3, dotenv
- Files: `backend/src/server.js`, `backend/src/db.js`
- Implementation notes:
  - `server.js` configures Express, JSON parsing, CORS, and mounts routers.
  - `db.js` uses `sqlite` + `sqlite3` to open/create `data/app.db`, creates tables (`documents`, `document_chunks`, `chats`) and ensures columns via migrations.
- Commands:

  cd backend
  npm install
  npm run dev

- Verification: server logs `Backend running on http://localhost:PORT` and file `backend/data/app.db` exists.

Step 3 — File upload and parsing
- Tech: `multer` (file handling), `pdf-parse` (PDF), `mammoth` (Word), `csv-parse` (CSV), Node Buffer APIs
- Files: `backend/src/routes/upload.js`, `backend/src/services/documentParser.js`
- Implementation:
  - Frontend sends `FormData` with key `documents` to `/api/upload`.
  - `multer.memoryStorage()` reads files into memory; `parseDocument()` extracts text and numeric metadata depending on extension.
  - Store extracted text in `documents.content`, numeric metadata in `numeric_data`.
- Important limits: upload size `15 MB` and max 3 files configured in `upload.js`.
- Example snippet (simplified):

  const parsed = await parseDocument(file);
  const chunks = chunkDocument(parsed.text);
  const embeddings = await generateEmbeddings(chunks.map(c => c.content));

Step 4 — Chunking & retrieval prep
- Tech: custom algorithm (term vectors), fallback sparse vectors, chunking rules
- Files: `backend/src/services/retrievalService.js`
- Implementation:
  - Break documents into paragraphs; group into chunks under ~1600 characters.
  - Compute a sparse term-frequency vector per chunk (tokenization + stop words removal).
  - Provide `selectRelevantChunks(question, chunks)` that scores via overlap, sparse cosine similarity, and dense embedding cosine (if available).
- Why: enables local retrieval even without OpenAI embeddings; good for small projects and deterministic behavior.

Step 5 — Embeddings (optional, improves relevance)
- Tech: OpenAI Embeddings API via `openai` npm package
- Files: `backend/src/services/embeddingService.js`
- Implementation:
  - `generateEmbeddings(inputs)` calls OpenAI `embeddings.create` with `text-embedding-3-small` (configurable via `.env`).
  - Store returned vectors as JSON in `document_chunks.embedding_json`.
- Notes: if `OPENAI_API_KEY` not set, embeddings calls return `null` and the code falls back to sparse vectors.

Step 6 — Answer generation & structured queries
- Tech: OpenAI Chat Completions (optional) + local extractive answerer
- Files: `backend/src/services/llmService.js`, `backend/src/services/structuredAnswerService.js`
- Implementation:
  - On a query: retrieve relevant chunks via `selectRelevantChunks()`.
  - If OpenAI key present: call `client.chat.completions.create` with a system prompt instructing the model to answer only from the provided context.
  - If no key: run `buildExtractiveAnswer()` that scores sentences for relevance and returns top sentence(s).
  - `structuredAnswerService` inspects numeric/CSV-like data and handles aggregate queries (count, average), filtering, and unique value extraction.
- Example: `answerQuestion(question, docs, chunks)` returns `{ status, answer, sources }`.

Step 7 — Persisting chat history
- Tech: SQLite
- Files: `backend/src/routes/query.js`, `backend/src/routes/files.js`
- Implementation: `QUERY` route inserts `user` and `assistant` messages into `chats` table. `files` route can clear chats when documents deleted.

Step 8 — Frontend integration
- Tech: React, fetch API, Vite
- Files: `frontend/src/components/FileUpload.jsx`, `frontend/src/components/ChatBox.jsx`, `frontend/src/App.jsx`
- Implementation:
  - `FileUpload` handles `onChange` file selection, constructs `FormData`, POSTs to `/api/upload`, and updates uploaded files list.
  - `ChatBox` fetches `/api/query/history` and displays messages; sends user questions to `/api/query`.
  - UI state sync: after deleting all files or when files length changes, `historyVersion` increments to refresh chat history.
- Run:

  cd frontend
  npm install
  npm run dev

Step 9 — Testing & verification
- Manual tests:
  - Upload sample PDF/CSV/TXT and ask direct questions found in the content.
  - Verify that `chats` table stores messages and that files show in UI.
- Suggestion: add automated unit tests around `documentParser` and `retrievalService`.

Step 10 — Deployment considerations
- Small project: run backend on Node host and serve frontend with static hosting or reverse-proxy.
- For production scale:
  - Move embeddings and vector search to a vector DB (Pinecone, Weaviate) for efficient NN queries.
  - Add authentication and per-user document isolation.
  - Offload file storage to S3 or blob storage for large files.

3. Implementation Details per Tech (concise)

- Express: lightweight REST API; routing split for clarity.
- Multer: in-memory file buffering enabling fast processing without writing temp files.
- pdf-parse / mammoth: reliable server-side text extraction for PDF/Word.
- csv-parse: robust CSV parsing to convert to structured rows for `structuredAnswerService`.
- SQLite: zero-config local persistence; good for demo and submission.
- OpenAI client: used for embeddings and chat; code checks for `OPENAI_API_KEY` and falls back when absent.
- React + Vite: fast frontend dev + optimized build; uses relative `/api` calls for simplicity.

4. Example Applications and Use Cases

- Research assistant: load academic papers and ask questions grounded in the PDFs.
- Financial analysis: upload CSVs and ask for aggregates (averages, counts, trends) via structured queries.
- Document QA for support teams: upload product manuals and let support agents query specifics.

5. Troubleshooting and Tips

- Increase `multer` limits for large files; consider streaming parsing for very large PDFs.
- Reset DB: delete `backend/data/app.db` to start fresh.
- If LLM errors: check environment variable `OPENAI_API_KEY` and model names in `.env`.
- For reproducible dev environment, run backend and frontend in separate terminals.

6. Next Steps & Enhancements

- Add unit tests and CI for parsing and retrieval.
- Add authentication and per-user document isolation.
- Replace SQLite with production DB and a vector DB for embeddings.
- Improve UI with progress indicators and chunk-preview for sources.

